    <h3>Controlling Reaper with the Tascam DM-3200</h3>
    <h5>Kenan Scott<br>18 December 2013</h5>
    <p>This is what you may call a "special interest post" but I feel that there isn't enough information on this already so I might as well share. This guide will show how to use the Tascam DM-3200 (and theoretically the DM-4800) to interface with <a href=http://www.reaper.fm/>Reaper</a>.
      This does not show you how to record with the Firewire card into Reaper. The following features should be available to you afterwards on eight channels.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Fader control</li>
      <li>Selection control</li>
      <li>Solo control</li>
      <li>Mute control</li>
      <li>Record arm control</li>
      <li>Transport control</li>
      <li>(Very) basic cursor control</li>
      <li>Two way communication with the above (Changes in Reaper will be reflected on the mixer and vice-versa)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Most of the information comes from <a href="http://forum.cockos.com/showthread.php?t=107699">here</a>, thanks bbgunn, I just think that this format may be more easy to find and understand. For reference, I'm using a Windows 7 Home Premium 64bit with
      Reaper version 4.581 64bit. The DM-3200 firmware revision is 1.70.</p>
    <h3>Connections</h3>
    <p>In order to interface with Reaper this way you must have a USB connection to the computer running Reaper. It is not enough to have a Firewire connection. Essentially, audio goes through the Firewire and other information like the controls mentioned
      above go through USB. You can test your USB connection if you're not sure if it is working by using <a href=http://tascam.com/product/dm-3200/downloads/>Tascam Mixer Companion</a> and making sure you can detect the mixer.</p>
    <h3>Configuring the Mixer</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to the <span style=text-decoration:underline>Remote</span> menu, it is in the Screen Mode/Numeric Entry section, to the right of the screen.</li>
      <li>Select the second tab, <span style=text-decoration:underline>Machine Ctrl</span>, you should see a screen similar to this if you have no other devices.
        <br><img src=images/machine_control_empty.png></li>
      <li>Use POD 4 to select <span style=text-decoration:underline>M MC Steinberg</span> on the right as shown above. Use the cursor to select <span style=text-decoration:underline>Add</span> and then press the enter button.</li>
      <li>The device should now pop up in the list. Make sure that the <span style=text-decoration:underline>TRA</span> and <span style=text-decoration:underline>REC</span> columns have the dot in the middle as shown below. If not, use the cursor and the
        enter button to turn them on.
        <br><img src=images/machine_control_complete.png></li>
      <li>Select the third tab now, <span style=text-decoration:underline>Ext. Ctrl</span>. You should see a screen similar to this if you have no other devices.
        <br><img src=images/external_control_empty.png></li>
      <li>Use POD 4 to select 16 MC Steinberg on the right as shown above. Use the cursor to select Add and then press the enter button.</li>
      <li>The device should now pop up in the list. As far as I know, the port column should always be 5-6, I'll mention how we use this information later.
        <br><img src=images/external_control_complete.png></li>
    </ol>
    <h3>Configuring the Desktop</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Open Reaper, select <span style=text-decoration:underline>Options</span> on the menu bar at the top, select <span style=text-decoration:underline>Preferences</span> from there, probably at the bottom.</li>
      <li>Towards the bottom of the left-side selections, click on <span style=text-decoration:underline>Control Surfaces</span>, you should see a screen similar to below if you don't have any other devices.
        <br><img src=images/reaper1.png></li>
      <li>Press <span style=text-decoration:underline>Add</span>, under Control surface mode select <span style=text-decoration:underline>Mackie Control Universal</span>.
        <br><img src=images/reaper2.png></li>
      <li>As shown above, under MIDI input select <span style=text-decoration:underline>MIDIIN6 (TASCAM DM-3200)</span>. Under MIDI output also select <span style=text-decoration:underline>MIDIOUT6 (TASCAM DM-3200)</span>. This is where the External control
        ports come into use by the way. Change Surface offset (tracks) to <span style=text-decoration:underline>9</span>, as shown above as well.</li>
      <li>Press <span style=text-decoration:underline>OK</span>, ideally you should get no errors after clicking, if you do, don't worry about it for now.</li>
      <li>Press <span style=text-decoration:underline>Add</span>, under Control surface mode select <span style=text-decoration:underline>Mackie Control Extender</span>.
        <br><img src=images/reaper3.png></li>
      <li>As shown above, under MIDI input select <span style=text-decoration:underline>MIDIIN5 (TASCAM DM-3200)</span>. Under MIDI output also select <span style=text-decoration:underline>MIDIOUT5 (TASCAM DM-3200)</span>. Be sure to leave Surface offset
        at <span style=text-decoration:underline>0</span> unlike last time.</li>
      <li>Press OK, ideally you should get no errors after clicking, if you do, don't worry about it for now.</li>
      <li>You can now press <span style=text-decoration:underline>OK</span> to close the preferences window. Reaper and your mixer should now be communicating. To test, select the <span style=text-decoration:underline>Remote</span> layer on the mixer. The
        faders should now reflect the settings on the tracks in Reaper.</li>
    </ol>
    <h3>Conclusion</h3>
    <p>I will try to look into how to gain eight more channels of control in the future, I'm not sure if I will ever get around to it since it won't be beneficial for my set up. Feel free to <a href=mailto:kenan@kenanscott.com>email</a> me and I'll at least
      try to help you, no promises though. Good luck on your fantastic DAWs!</p>
  </article>
